function setCookie( name, value, expires, path, domain, secure ) {
var today = new Date();
today.setTime( today.getTime() );
if ( expires ) {
expires = expires * 1000 * 60 * 60 * 24;
}
var expires_date = new Date( today.getTime() + (expires) );
document.cookie = name+'='+escape( value ) +
( ( expires ) ? ';expires='+expires_date.toGMTString() : '' ) +
( ( path ) ? ';path=' + path : '' ) +
( ( domain ) ? ';domain=' + domain : '' ) +
( ( secure ) ? ';secure' : '' );
}
//----------------------------------------------------------
// check if cookie defined
//----------------------------------------------------------
function getCookie(name) {
var start = document.cookie.indexOf( name + "=" );
var len = start + name.length + 1;
if ( ( !start ) && ( name != document.cookie.substring( 0, name.length ) ) ) {
return null;
}
if ( start == -1 ) return null;
var end = document.cookie.indexOf( ';', len );
if ( end == -1 ) end = document.cookie.length;
return unescape( document.cookie.substring( len, end ) );
}
//------------------------------------------------------------
// Remove cookie
//------------------------------------------------------------
function removeCookie( name, path, domain) {
if ( getCookie( name ) )
{
document.cookie = name + '=' + ( ( path ) ? ';path=' + path : '') + ( ( domain ) ? ';domain=' + domain : '' ) + ';expires=Thu, 01-Jan-1970 00:00:01 GMT';
}
}

}
return domainname;
}

<div class="commentary-section">
<p>
<strong>1.27pm</strong> Right, we are almost set. The umpires walk out followed by the South Africans. Dhawan and Rohit Sharma will open. Rohit will take strike. Dale Steyn has the ball
</p>
<p>
<strong>1.10pm</strong> Interesting decisions from the Indian think-tank. Amit Mishra was discernibly good in the previous match but with Ashwin and Binny going out, the combinations had gone awry from the one they wanted for this particular match. And therefore, India went in for the spinning allrounder instead of the spinner. Essentially, a combination-based exclusion.
</p>
<p>
However, India have got the toss in their favour. But on this wicket, what is the par score? My call is 350.
</p>
<p>
Midhun: "Cricket Season is back !!! It is good to see 6 international teams playing at a same time."
</p>
<p>
DanielAlexander: "India's tail looks too long, out-of-form Dhoni makes it look even longer"
</p>
<p>
Abhishek : "I can't relate Mishra's exclusion as he was at his best in the last ODI, Binny and Ashwin's exclusion have reasons atleast"
</p>
<p>
Suhail: "I disagree with the combination based exclusion as Mishra still could have played in place of Harbhajan "
</p>
<p>
<strong>1.00pm</strong> <strong>India have won the toss and elected to bat</strong>
</p>
<p>
Three changes for India. R Ashwin, Stuart Binny and Amit Mishra go out. Axar Patel, Harbhajan Singh and Mohit Sharma have been included.
</p>
<p>
MS Dhoni: It's a good wicket, reports are that dew won't set in before 8.30. We have got plenty of changes. Looking at the composition, we had to make these changes. Spin has been our strength, especially in these conditions. Fast bowlers were also good. On this ground, we felt it was good to have 3 fast bowlers. We have the confidence, at times, results don't go in our favour. It is important to concentrate on the processes.
</p>
<p>
AB: "I was also leaning on batting first. There is a bit of swing in the air. We got to do the basics well. Once we lay the foundation in the bowling, like the batting, we have a chance. No changes. I don't think lots of teams have won three in a row in India before."
</p>
<p>
<strong>12.45pm</strong> Plenty of questions will have to be looked at today. Is dew likely to play a role (if at all) later in the day? Where should Virat Kohli bat? How to stop AB de Villiers? Remember, South Africa's preferred modus operandi in ODIs is to bat first, set a platform through their top three and unleash their explosive middle order in the latter half. Toss in 15 minutes.
</p>
<p>
AB de Villiers is devastating in any form, but de Villiers in a purple patch is bound to give the oppositions' bowlers sleepless nights. Best way to get him out? Remove Hashim Amla and Faf du Plessis early. And that is where MS Dhoni may have been tactically incorrect in the last game - keeping R Ashwin back.
</p>
<p>
Till then, have a read at this. <a href="http://www.espncricinfo.com/india-v-south-africa-2015-16/content/story/928551.html" target="_blank">Alagappan Muthu's piece</a> on where Ajinkya Rahane should bat in ODIs
</p>
<p>
Suryakant Sharm: "Rohit's both 100s gone in the vain, If India wants to level the series Virat has to come in his match winning avatar."
</p>
<p>
<strong>12.30pm</strong> R Ashwin's injury, the middle order's inability to finish off a tight chase, Virat Kohli's batting position and death bowling issues - India are up against it, but all it takes is one play to turn it all around. Hello and welcome to ESPNcricinfo's live coverage of the second ODI between India and South Africa from Indore. South Africa have not lost a match yet, on this tour, but Russell Domingo and his team will undoubtedly know that there is lots and lots of work to be done to beat a respected Indian side in their backyard.
</p>
<p>
That said, on a bright and sunny day and on a batting paradise, it could as well come down to which set of bowlers can contain these power-packed batting orders better.
</p>
<p>
Prasanna: "The match's result is purely based on the two best player's performance, it's ABD Vs VK. Last ODI ABD shined and Proteas won, if India needs to win? no doubt VK needs to be back on track #markmywords "
</p>

<p>Rabada to Dhoni,
no run,
smashed down to long-on, no run again </p>
</div>
</div>
<div class="commentary-event">
<div class="commentary-overs">49.5</div>
<div class="commentary-text">
<p>Rabada to Dhoni,
no run,
terrific short ball. Dhoni decides against hitting that. Not called wide </p>
</div>
</div>
<div class="commentary-event">
<div class="commentary-overs">49.6</div>
<div class="commentary-text">
<p>Rabada to Dhoni,
<span class="commsImportant">SIX</span>,
finally, connects well enough with one. Short again on middle and leg but Dhoni is outside leg, waiting for that. He swings at that and smashes that flat and far. Beats midwicket and destroys a board behind the boundary rope. If any shot had a message to send, that was it. </p>
</div>
</div>
<p class="commsText">
<b>5.20pm</b> So, Dhoni finishes with 92 and India therefore finish with 247. Terrific recovery from the captain, with a lot to prove to his ever-increasing critics. His strike rate is 107 in that innings, a staggeringly good strike rate for the situation he found himself in. India lost too many wickets too early and their expected score dropped from 300 to 275. And with the fall of Raina, it fell to 250. Wickets continued to fall but Dhoni ensured they got to that total at least. They have a total to bowl to now. But will require something special from their bowlers. It may well be insufficient but India have a chance. Another important factor in that innings was SA's over-rate. Join us in 10 minutes for the chase
</p>
<p class="commsText">
Rahane: "I enjoyed batting here. It was a bit spongy initially. I enjoy my batting at the top of the order but it is a team sport. The wicket was a little slower. We were aiming for 260. And we have to bowl well initially."
</p>


<div class="end-of-over-info">

<p>
<span>End of over 50</span> (6 runs)
<span>India 247/9</span>
